 2011 uprisings side by side with the revolutions of the 1970s, particularly the Iranian Revolution, Bayat reveals a profound global shift in the nature of protest: as acceptance of neoliberal policy has spread, radical revolutionary impulses have diminished. Protestors call for reform rather than fundamental transformation. By tracing the contours and illuminating the meaning of the 2011 uprisings, Bayat gives us the book needed to explain and understand our post-Arab Spring world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aArab Spring, 2010-. 0aPolitics and government. 0aRevolutionsxArab countries. 0aRevolutionszArab countries. 0aRevolutions. 4aArab Spring. 4aArab revolution. 4aEgypt. 4aIranian revolution. 4aTunisia. 4aneoliberalism. 4arefo-lution. 4auprisings. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360307340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503603073423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503603073.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles